ource/sn83045830/1907-10-13/ed-1/?fo=json&sp=9"}, {"number": 10, "url": null}, {"number": 11, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045830/1907-10-13/ed-1/?fo=json&sp=11"}, {"number": 12, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045830/1907-10-13/ed-1/?fo=json&sp=12"}], "perpage": 1, "perpage_options": [25, 50, 100, 150], "previous": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045830/1907-10-13/ed-1/?fo=json&sp=9", "results": "10 - 10", "to": 10, "total": 14}, "previous_resource": {"label": "Previous Issue", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045830/1907-10-12/ed-1/?fo=json&sp=1"}, "related_items": [{"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/gm71002167", "http://www.loc.gov/item/gm71002167/", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/e89a1847-aa91-509a-8207-dbba8ae11ded", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.gmd/g3884h.ar145000", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/g3884h.ar145000/"], "campaigns": [], "date": "1781", "dates": ["1781"], "description": ["\"This topographic pen-and-ink and watercolor manuscript map of Hampton, Virginia, and its surroundings was created in 1781. The area shown on the map extends from the Chesapeake Bay westward to the mouth of the James River. The map shows the mouths of the Back (i.e., Black), James, and Elizabeth Rivers, as well as the towns of Hampton and Newport News. Other features include fortifications, houses in the area, roads, windmills, a Corps de garde (guardhouse) near Old Point Comfort, and vegetation. Scale is given in toises, an old French unit measuring about 1.95 meters. The map has a watermark in the shape of a fleur-de-lis, surmounting a scroll with three bars. North is oriented to the upper right, and relief is shown by hachures. Hampton was founded in 1610, and has claims to being the longest continuously occupied English settlement in the present-day United States. The map is from the Rochambeau Collection at the Library of Congress, which consists of 40 manuscript maps, 26 printed maps, and a manuscript atlas that belonged to Jean-Baptiste-Donatien de Vimeur, comte de Rochambeau (1725-1807), commander in chief of the French expeditionary army (1780-82) during the American Revolution. Some of the maps were used by Rochambeau during the war. Dating from 1717 to 1795, the maps cover much of eastern North America, from Newfoundland and Labrador in the north to Haiti in the south. The collection includes maps of cities, maps showing Revolutionary War battles and military campaigns, and early state maps from the 1790s.\" World Digital Library."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-04-29T15:39:46.170Z", "group": ["gmd.mar", "catalog-split-12", "catalog", "general-maps", "main-catalog-split-12"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/gm71002167/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd388/g3884/g3884h/ar145000.gif", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmd388/g3884/g3884h/ar145000.gif#h=150&w=254", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd388:g3884:g3884h:ar145000/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=817&w=1383", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmd388:g3884:g3884h:ar145000/full/pct:25/0/default.jpg#h=1635&w=2766"], "index": 10, "language": ["french"], "location": ["virginia", "newport news", "hampton roads", "hampton", "united states"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "image/tiff", "image/jpeg", "image/jp2"], "number": ["2025-06-07t18:28:54.600000", "2022-07-14t10:52:13", "gm71002167"], "online_format": ["image"], "original_format": ["map"], "partof": ["rochambeau map collection", "geography and map division", "france in america", "american revolution and its era: maps and charts of north america and the west indies, 1750-1789", "military battles and campaigns", "world digital library", "catalog"], "score": 55.725147, "shelf_id": "G3884.H2 1781 .C3", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["virginia", "hampton roads", "newport news", "hampton (va.)", "hampton", "early works to 1800", "maps, manuscript", "newport news (va.)", "united states", "hampton roads (va.)"], "timestamp": "2026-04-29T16:36:27.580Z", "title": "Carte des environs d'Hampton", "type": ["cartographic"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/gm71002167/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/gvhs01.vhs00071/", "http://www.loc.gov/item/gvhs01.vhs00071/", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.ndlpcoop/gvhs01.vhs00071", "http://www.loc.gov/item/001-CABIB20005981/"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["sneden, robert knox"], "date": "1862-04-01", "dates": ["1862-04-01"], "description": ["Shows area of Virginia Peninsula between Newport News and Big Bethel to the north and Fortress Monroe to the south as McClellan prepared to move his forces toward Richmond."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2020-09-23T16:30:14.530Z", "group": ["gmd_vhs.mar", "virginia-historical-society-maps"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/gvhs01.vhs00071/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmdvhs/gvhs/gvhs01/vhs00071.gif", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/gmd/gmdvhs/gvhs/gvhs01/vhs00071.gif#h=206&w=150", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmdvhs:gvhs:gvhs01:vhs00071/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=300&w=218", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:gmd:gmdvhs:gvhs:gvhs01:vhs00071/full/pct:25/0/default.jpg#h=600&w=436"], "index": 11, "language": ["english"], "location": ["virginia", "newport news", "big bethel", "fort monroe", "hampton", "united states"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "image/tiff", "image/jpeg", "image/jp2"], "number": ["2002-12-06t16:44:16"], "online_format": ["image"], "original_format": ["map"], "partof": ["civil war maps", "geography and map division", "american memory", "military battles and campaigns"], "score": 37.735207, "shelf_id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/001-CABIB20005981/", "site": ["ammem"], "subject": ["virginia", "maps", "newport news", "history", "big bethel", "big bethel (hampton, va.)